      {
        "content": "The visual representation in the study uses specific color coding and shapes to denote the status of chimpanzees during the social transmission phase: trained demonstrators are red squares, skilled individuals are dark-blue circles, individuals attempting but not yet skilled are turquoise circles, and naive individuals are white circles. Arrows indicate the direction of observation from the observed to the observer, with fully black arrows representing 100 or more observations. This visual schema allows for a quick assessment of the social network dynamics and information flow.",
        "title": "Visual coding scheme for social transmission networks",
