      },
      {
        "content": "The study highlights that many chimpanzees frequently observed others but never learned the skill, a pattern that aligns with the baseline phase results where no chimpanzee was successful. This attests to the inherent difficulty of the sequential task, suggesting that observation provides necessary information but does not guarantee comprehension or motor execution capability. The difficulty level serves as a control, ensuring that successful learning is not trivial and requires significant cognitive processing.",
