      {
        "content": "Table 1 provides detailed observation records for chimpanzees in both Group 1 and Group 2. It lists specific individuals alongside their number of observations, skill acquisition status (0 for no, 1 for yes), total observation time in hours, rate of observation, and number of solves. \n\nFor Group 1, key examples include: Rusty, who acquired the skill after 252 observations with 49.17 hours of total observation time and 1 solve; Rachel, who acquired it after 9 observations with 2.32 hours of total observation time and 926 solves; and Regina, who had 166 observations, 45.77 hours of observation time, and 1,048 solves. Several others, such as BJ (205 observations), Gonzaga (99 observations), Irene (153 observations), and Renate (406 observations), failed to acquire the skill despite extensive exposure, highlighting individual variation in learning efficiency.\n\nFor Group 2, the table includes individuals such as Charity, who acquired the skill after 209 observations with 69.38 hours of observation time and 23 solves. Others in Group 2 like Carol (17 observations), Claire (0 observations), and Coco (3 observations) did not acquire the skill. \n\nAdditionally, the source describes visualization conventions where fully black represents 100 or more observations, red squares indicate trained demonstrators, dark-blue circles represent skilled individuals, turquoise circles represent those attempting but not yet skilled, and white circles represent naive individuals (with or without receiving observation arrows).\n\n[Prior understanding, corrected May 24, 2026, 08:16 PM]: Table 1 provides detailed observation records for chimpanzees in Group 1, listing specific individuals alongside their number of observations, skill acquisition status (0 or 1), total observation time in hours, rate of observation, and number of solves. For instance, Rusty acquired the skill after 252 observations with a total observation time of 49.17 hours and achieved 1,048 solves, while Rachel acquired it after only 9 observations with 2.32 hours of total observation time and 926 solves. This data highlights significant individual variation in the efficiency of learning and subsequent performance.",
