        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "Daisey 2 75 0 71.38 1.05 0 Danny 2 43 1 71.38 9.85 3 David 2 0 0 71.38 0 0 Debbie 2 13 0 71.38 0.18 0 Diana 2 93 1 36.11 2.58 377 Dizzy 2 188 0 71.38 2.63 0 Dolly 2 19 1 29.2 0.65 1,381 Donna 2 25 0 71.38 0.35 0 Dora 2 33 0 71.38 0.46 0 Doug 2 0 0 71.38 0 0 Jacky 2 239 0 71.38 3.35 0 Jane 2 19 0 71.38 0.27 0 John 2 174 0 71.38 2.44 0 Jones 2 274 0 71.38 3.84 0 Judy 2 135 0 71.38 1.89 0 LittleJenkins 2 49 1 50.4 0.97 232 Maggie 2 289 0 71.38 4.05 0 Martin 2 123 1 54.63 1.85 1 Mary 2 59 0 71.38 0.83 0 Masya 2 13 0 71.38 0.18 0 Max 2 124 0 71.38 1.74 0 Maxine 2 31 0 71.38 0.43 0 Nature Human Behaviour | Volume 8 | May 2024 | 891–902 895 Article https://doi.org/10.1038/s41562-024-01836-5 Table 1 (continued) | Chimpanzees’ observation records and successful operations Chimpanzee Group No. of observations Acquired skill Total observation time Rate of observation No. of solves (0, no; 1, yes) (hours) May 2 301 1 69.38 4.47 3 Mikey 2 41 0 71.38 0.57 0 Misha 2 43 0 71.38 0.6 0 Moyo 2 39 0 71.38 0.55 0 Nikkie 2 32 1 49.15 0.65 213 Nina 2 8 0 71.38 0.11 0 Noel 2 14 0 71.38 0.2 0 Pan 2 0 0 71.38 0 0 Pippaa 2 NA NA NA NA 3,453 Tess 2 14 1 54.78 0.33 179 Tilly 2 16 1 38.35 0.42 159 Trixie 2 11 0 71.38 0.15 0 Violet 2 38 0 71.38 0.53 0 Vis 2 25 0 71.38 0.35 0 Zsabu 2 9 0 71.38 0.13 0 a Trained individual, thus not taken into account for detecting social learning signatures. NA, not applicable. The table shows the number of observations prior to the first solve for those that acquired the skill and prior to the final solve for those that did not; the time the chimpanzees had to make observations, which is the time until the first solve or the time until the final solve; the rate of observation (prior to the first solve for solvers); and the total number of solves for each individual. estimated as the parameter s, defined as the rate of learning per unit to solve the task at least 1 + 10 × 0.461 = 5.61× faster than a comparable",
        "title": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf - Part 12/41",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:17:42.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "The study quantified the extent of social transmission (%ST) by converting the parameter 's' into an estimated percentage, revealing that between 18.5% and 100% of learning events occurred via social transmission. This wide range underscores the dominance of social learning over asocial discovery in this context, providing a statistical baseline for the efficiency of cultural transmission in the chimpanzee groups.",
        "title": "Estimated percentage of social transmission events",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:18:55.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "Statistical analysis found no support for the influence of sex, social rank, or age on the rate of either social or asocial learning, with all factors showing less than 30% support. This indicates that the capacity for social learning in this task was distributed relatively evenly across demographic categories, challenging assumptions that certain social positions or ages confer a distinct learning advantage.",
        "title": "Demographic factors and learning rates",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:18:55.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "The researchers utilized network-based diffusion analysis to track the spread of the new skill within the chimpanzee groups. This analytical method allows for the identification of social learning pathways by correlating the acquisition of the behavior with the social network structure of the group, rather than just temporal proximity.\n\nThe researchers employed Network-Based Diffusion Analysis (NBDA) to analyze the transmission data, utilizing the R statistical environment version 3.6.1 and the NBDA package version 0.8.3. This statistical approach was chosen to infer social transmission by determining if the diffusion of the skill followed the connections of a social network, which represented the opportunities for learning between dyads of chimpanzees. This analytical method allows for the identification of social learning pathways by correlating the acquisition of the behavior with the social network structure of the group, rather than just temporal proximity.\n\nThe researchers utilized network-based diffusion analysis to track the spread of the new skill within the chimpanzee groups. This analytical method allows for the identification of social learning pathways by correlating the acquisition of the behavior with the social network structure of the group, rather than just temporal proximity.\n\nThe researchers employed Network-Based Diffusion Analysis (NBDA) to analyze the transmission data, utilizing the R statistical environment version 3.6.1 and the NBDA package version 0.8.3. This statistical approach was chosen to infer social transmission by determining if the diffusion of the skill followed the connections of a social network, which represented the opportunities for learning between dyads of chimpanzees.\n\nObservations indicated that the chimpanzees were motivated to solve the apparatus and retrieve food rewards. In each group, chimpanzees once managed to break off the lid of the apparatus during the first week of the baseline phase, allowing them to freely forage on stored peanuts. \n\nFigure 2 presents observational records of chimpanzees who mastered the skill in Group 1 and Group 2. Red dots represent events where individuals observed a group member successfully operating the apparatus. The number following each chimpanzee's name indicates the number of observations they made prior to their first successful apparatus operation. All chimpanzees who eventually mastered the skill had observed a successful token insertion and subsequent reward retrieval at least once.\n\nFigure 3 illustrates the social transmission of the new skill in the two communities. The blackness of the arrows is proportional to the number of observations, visualizing the flow of information and skill acquisition through the social network.\n\nThe researchers utilized network-based diffusion analysis (NBDA) to track the spread of the new skill within the chimpanzee groups. This analytical method allows for the identification of social learning pathways by correlating the acquisition of the behavior with the social network structure of the group, rather than just temporal proximity.\n\nThe researchers employed Network-Based Diffusion Analysis (NBDA) to analyze the transmission data, utilizing the R statistical environment version 3.6.1 and the NBDA package version 0.8.3. This statistical approach was chosen to infer social transmission by determining if the diffusion of the skill followed the connections of a social network, which represented the opportunities for learning between dyads of chimpanzees.\n\nThe Network-Based Diffusion Analysis (NBDA) supported the hypothesis that chimpanzees relied on social learning to acquire a skill they could not master through asocial learning alone. This conclusion is reinforced by Supplementary Table 1, which confirms that the observed acquisition patterns align with social transmission models rather than individual innovation rates.\n\nObservations indicated that the chimpanzees were motivated to solve the apparatus and retrieve food rewards. In each group, chimpanzees once managed to break off the lid of the apparatus during the first week of the baseline phase, allowing them to freely forage on stored peanuts. \n\nFigure 2 presents observational records of chimpanzees who mastered the skill in Group 1 and Group 2. Red dots represent events where individuals observed a group member successfully operating the apparatus. The number following each chimpanzee's name indicates the number of observations they made prior to their first successful apparatus operation. All chimpanzees who eventually mastered the skill had observed a successful token insertion and subsequent reward retrieval at least once.\n\nFigure 3 illustrates the social transmission of the new skill in the two communities. The blackness of the arrows is proportional to the number of observations, visualizing the flow of information and skill acquisition through the social network.",
        "title": "Use of network-based diffusion analysis in the study",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:07:01.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "The rate of social transmission was best predicted by the number of task solutions observed, which received 50.4% support in the model averaging. The number of individuals observed solving the task was the second-best predictor with 34.7% support, suggesting that witnessing the mechanical action repeatedly is more informative than simply seeing multiple different individuals succeed.",
        "title": "Predictors of social transmission rate",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:08.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "The researchers decomposed the learning process into two stages: first, learning to interact with the apparatus, and second, learning to actually solve it. Evidence suggested that the rate of starting to interact with the task was related to the number of successes observed, with this effect being notably stronger in Group 2, indicating a potential group-specific dynamic in initial engagement.",
        "title": "Two-stage learning process decomposition",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:20.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "In the two-stage learning model, the parameter for the second stage (solving) was significantly higher than the first (interacting), with a model-averaged estimate of 2.12 for s2 compared to 0.40 for s1 in Group 2. The 95% confidence interval for the ratio s2/s1 ranged from 1.4 to 85.3, suggesting that once chimpanzees began interacting, the social transmission of the actual solution mechanism was much more potent than the initial attraction to the device.",
        "title": "Strength of social transmission in solving vs. interacting",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:20.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "Models in which the social learning rates for the two stages were equal (s1 = s2) received the best support overall, suggesting that social transmission operated consistently across both groups despite the nuanced differences in the two-stage breakdown. This indicates a robust underlying mechanism of social learning that applies to both initial engagement and final skill acquisition.",
        "title": "Consistency of social transmission across groups",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:20.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that the finding that 'number of task solutions observed' is a better predictor than 'number of individuals observed' highlights the importance of mechanical clarity over social diversity. This suggests chimpanzees are tracking the causal relationship between action and reward through repetition, rather than just conforming to a behavior because many peers are doing it.",
        "title": "Agent observation on mechanical clarity vs. social conformity",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:20.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) find the lack demographic effects (sex, rank, age) significant because it isolates the cognitive mechanism of social learning from social hierarchy dynamics. This suggests that the 'know-how' transmission in this specific task was accessible to all group members regardless of their social standing, which is crucial for understanding the potential for cumulative culture in egalitarian contexts.",
        "title": "Agent interpretation of demographic neutrality in learning",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:20.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) observe that the two-stage breakdown reveals a 'gateway' effect where social cues strongly drive initial interaction, but the transition to successful solving requires a different or intensified level of social information. The stronger effect in Group 2 for the initial stage might reflect differences in group cohesion or the specific modeling behavior of the trained individual in that group.",
        "title": "Agent analysis of the two-stage learning gateway",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:21.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "Asocial learning received negligible support in the model averaging, with an Akaike weight of only 0.6%. Although only four models were fitted, the researchers used the 95% confidence intervals for the social learning parameter 's' to rigorously quantify the strength of evidence against purely asocial learning, effectively ruling out individual discovery as the primary mechanism for skill acquisition in this task.\n\nAsocial learning received negligible support in the model averaging, with an Akaike weight of only 0.6%. Although only four models were fitted, the researchers used the 95% confidence intervals for the social learning parameter 's' to rigorously quantify the strength of evidence against purely asocial learning, effectively ruling out individual discovery as the primary mechanism for skill acquisition in this task. The study concluded that social transmission definitely occurred because all supported models estimated a lower 95% confidence interval limit for the social learning parameter 's' at greater than zero. The least supported model had an Akaike weight of 5 × 10^-7, providing robust statistical evidence that the spread of the skill was driven by social mechanisms rather than chance or independent innovation.",
        "title": "Negligible support for asocial learning",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:53.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "I (agent) notice that the study's design specifically isolates 'innovatable' vs 'non-innovatable' skills by providing a three-month baseline period where no chimpanzee solved the puzzle. This control period is critical for establishing that the subsequent learning was truly dependent on social information rather than latent individual discovery.\n\nI (agent) notice that the study's design specifically isolates 'innovatable' vs 'non-innovatable' skills by presenting the sequential task to two chimpanzee groups in their natural woodland enclosures for a prolonged baseline period of three months. During this time, no chimpanzee solved the puzzle, establishing a control condition for individual learning capabilities and ensuring that subsequent learning was truly dependent on social information rather than latent individual discovery.",
        "title": "Agent observation on experimental control period significance",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:07:06.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "When conditioning on the absolute observation network, the social learning parameter 's' had a model-averaged estimate of 0.023, with a 95% confidence interval ranging from 0.009 to 0.58. This corresponds to an estimated percentage of social transmission (%ST) between 8.1% and 47.4%, providing a quantitative range for the efficiency of social learning in this specific ecological and experimental context.",
        "title": "Quantified social transmission parameters",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:20:08.000Z",
