      {
        "content": "The statistical model strongly favored the absolute observation network over the group network, receiving 65.3 times more support. This finding confirms that social transmission in this context follows the specific pattern of direct observations of successful task solutions, rather than general group membership or broader social proximity. The precision of the absolute network indicates that chimpanzees are tracking specific mechanical demonstrations.\n\nThe statistical model strongly favored the absolute observation network over the group network, receiving 65.3 times more support. This finding confirms that social transmission in this context follows the specific pattern of direct observations of successful task solutions, rather than general group membership or broader social proximity. The precision of the absolute network indicates that chimpanzees are tracking specific mechanical demonstrations. This critical methodological finding suggests that chimpanzees are not just learning from 'anyone in the group' but are specifically attending to the mechanical success of individuals, reinforcing the idea that the content of the demonstration (the solution) is more important than the social identity of the demonstrator in this specific task.\n\nThe statistical model strongly favored the absolute observation network over the group network, receiving 65.3 times more support. This finding confirms that social transmission in this context follows the specific pattern of direct observations of successful task solutions, rather than general group membership or broader social proximity. The precision of the absolute network indicates that chimpanzees are tracking specific mechanical demonstrations.\n\nSpecific statistical estimates for the social transmission parameter (s) in the absolute observation network yielded a model-averaged estimate of 0.023 (95% CI: 0.009–0.58), corresponding to an estimated percentage of learning events occurring via social transmission (%ST) of 8.1–47.4%. Asocial learning received very little support (0.6%); however, given that only four models were fitted, the 95% confidence intervals for s were used to quantify the strength of evidence against purely asocial learning. Since all but the least supported model estimated a lower 95% CI limit for s at >0, the study concludes that social transmission of the task solution occurred.\n\nThis critical methodological finding suggests that chimpanzees are not just learning from 'anyone in the group' but are specifically attending to the mechanical success of individuals, reinforcing the idea that the content of the demonstration (the solution) is more important than the social identity of the demonstrator in this specific task.",
        "title": "Absolute observation network dominance",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:19:53.000Z",
