      {
        "content": "The experimental design involved independently training one chimpanzee in each group to function as a proficient conspecific demonstrator. This seeding strategy allowed researchers to test whether naive group members could socially learn 'know-how' that they had previously failed to re-innovate during the baseline phase, addressing a crucial capacity for cumulative cultural evolution (CCE) in humans.",
        "title": "Experimental design with seeded demonstrator",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:20:47.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "The results showed that 14 naive chimpanzees learned to operate a puzzle box after being exposed to skilled demonstrators. Crucially, these 14 individuals had failed to operate the same puzzle box during the preceding three months of exposure to all necessary materials, proving that individual exploration was insufficient for learning the task.\n\nThe results showed that 14 naive chimpanzees learned to operate a puzzle box after being exposed to skilled demonstrators. Crucially, during the preceding three-month baseline phase, absolutely none of the 66 resident chimpanzees across both groups succeeded in operating the apparatus even once, despite constant access to all necessary materials and social cues from other naive group members. This total failure rate served as definitive proof that individual learning combined with low-fidelity social cues (such as local and stimulus enhancement) was insufficient for acquiring the skill, and that individual exploration alone was insufficient for learning the task.\n\nThe results showed that 14 naive chimpanzees learned to operate a puzzle box after being exposed to skilled demonstrators. Crucially, during the preceding three-month baseline phase, absolutely none of the 66 resident chimpanzees across both groups succeeded in operating the apparatus even once, despite constant access to all necessary materials and social cues from other naive group members. This total failure rate served as definitive proof that individual learning combined with low-fidelity social cues (such as local and stimulus enhancement) was insufficient for acquiring the skill, and that individual exploration alone was insufficient for learning the task. Within the subsequent two-month social learning phase, these 14 individuals successfully acquired the skill, confirming that social learning was actively influencing the skill-acquisition process and enabling the acquisition of complex behaviors beyond individual innovative capabilities.",
        "title": "Empirical evidence: 14 naive chimpanzees learned via social exposure",
        "timestamp": "2026-05-25T00:07:01.000Z",
        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "All 14 chimpanzees who mastered the skill had observed a model successfully solving the task at least once prior to their own success. This universal prerequisite of at least one observation for all learners provides strong evidence that social information was necessary for innovation, ruling out the possibility of purely individual discovery in those who succeeded.\n\n[Prior understanding, corrected May 24, 2026, 08:16 PM]: All 14 chimpanzees who mastered the skill had observed a model successfully solving the task at least nine times prior to their own success. This minimum threshold of observation suggests that repeated exposure to the successful demonstration was a necessary precondition for learning, highlighting the importance of cumulative observational experience.\n\nAll 14 chimpanzees who mastered the skill had observed a model successfully solving the task at least once prior to their own success, establishing observation as a necessary prerequisite for innovation and ruling out purely individual discovery. However, statistical models show that a single observation was insufficient to produce a full social learning effect, receiving only 13.5% support. This implies that chimpanzees require cumulative evidence or repeated exposure (previously noted as a minimum of nine times for all learners) to decode the sequential mechanism, rather than achieving instant mastery through a single 'eureka' moment. Thus, while one observation is a baseline requirement, repeated exposure is the functional driver for successful skill acquisition.\n\nAll 14 chimpanzees who mastered the skill had observed a model successfully solving the task at least once prior to their own success, establishing observation as a necessary prerequisite for innovation and ruling out purely individual discovery. However, statistical models show that a single observation was insufficient to produce a full social learning effect, receiving only 13.5% support. This implies that chimpanzees require cumulative evidence or repeated exposure to decode the sequential mechanism, rather than achieving instant mastery through a single 'eureka' moment. Specifically, every successful chimpanzee observed the task at least nine times prior to their first success, with most learners observing significantly more than this minimum threshold. This indicates that a substantial volume of social evidence is required for successful skill acquisition.",
        "title": "Minimum observation threshold for skill mastery",
