        "source": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf"
      },
      {
        "content": "The study found a positive correlation between the number of observations and the speed of learning: the more times chimpanzees observed the task being solved, the faster they began interacting with the apparatus and the faster they solved it. This suggests that repeated social exposure not only facilitates initiation but also accelerates the mastery of the mechanical sequence.",
        "title": "Correlation between observation frequency and learning speed",
