 occurred in both groups. \n\nAdditionally, the study found an increase in the rate of solving per observation relative to the baseline asocial rate by seeding one proficient conspecific model (a female of middle rank and age) in each group. The 95% CI for s was 0.461–infinity, indicating that for every observation, chimpanzees’ learning rate increased by at least 0.461× the asocial baseline rate. This suggests chimpanzees can socially learn know-how they fail to re-innovate themselves, a capacity posited as crucial for Cumulative Cultural Evolution (CCE) in humans. The authors infer that 'response facilitation' (using a familiar action in a novel context) was likely at play. Experimental evidence regarding CCE in chimpanzees remains contested, particularly by ZLS proponents. In the social learning phase, 14 of 66 naive chimpanzees learned the skill from demonstrators within two months. Each skill adopter observed successful task manipulations at least nine times prior to learning. The more times chimpanzees observed the task being solved, the faster they started interacting with it and the faster they solved it.",
        "title": "chimpanzee-social-skill-acquisition-leeuwen-2024.pdf - Part 13/41",
