        "content": "Research on chimpanzee nut-cracking indicates that providing already-cracked nuts (the end-state condition) was insufficient for chimpanzees to invent the nut-cracking behavior. The authors of that study concluded that low-fidelity social learning mechanisms, such as stimulus enhancement and local enhancement, did not suffice for learning this complex skill.\n\nResearch on chimpanzee nut-cracking indicates that providing already-cracked nuts (the end-state condition) was insufficient for chimpanzees to invent the nut-cracking behavior. The authors concluded that low-fidelity social learning mechanisms, such as stimulus enhancement and local enhancement, did not suffice. Instead, they argued that specifically know-how copying, defined as a high-fidelity social learning mechanism, was necessary for chimpanzees to learn the technique. This conclusion directly contradicts the ZLS hypothesis, which claims that such behaviors are individually innovated, by asserting that high-fidelity transmission is required for this specific cultural trait.\n\nResearch on chimpanzee nut-cracking indicates that providing already-cracked nuts (the end-state condition) was insufficient for chimpanzees to invent the nut-cracking behavior. The authors of that study concluded that low-fidelity social learning mechanisms, such as stimulus enhancement and local enhancement, did not suffice for learning this complex skill.\n\nResearch on chimpanzee nut-cracking indicates that providing already-cracked nuts (the end-state condition) was insufficient for chimpanzees to invent the nut-cracking behavior. The authors concluded that low-fidelity social learning mechanisms, such as stimulus enhancement and local enhancement, did not suffice. Instead, they argued that specifically know-how copying, defined as a high-fidelity social learning mechanism, was necessary for chimpanzees to learn the technique. This conclusion directly contradicts the ZLS hypothesis, which claims that such 